        heading: 'Shoes: The Biggest Carry-On Challenge',
        body: 'Shoes are the single biggest obstacle to successful carry-on-only packing for two weeks, not because of volume (though they are bulky) but because of the psychology of thinking you need different shoes for different occasions. The practical two-week carry-on shoe formula: three pairs maximum, each one selected to serve multiple roles. Pair one: a neutral sneaker or leather shoe that works for casual daytime, light walking, and a casual dinner. Clean white sneakers have been crossing the business-casual line for years and work in most settings that don\'t require a suit. For men, a clean leather Oxford in a neutral brown or black color shifts from business casual to dinner-ready with a sock change. Pair two: a comfortable walking shoe or sandal for long sightseeing days, beach access, or hot weather. If the trip involves primarily city walking, this might be a second sneaker or a comfortable loafer. Pair three: the problem-solver — a pair that handles the trip\'s most formal requirement, whether that\'s a wedding, a business presentation, or a nice restaurant reservation. For most two-week trips, the three-pair rule accommodates every occasion. The packing trick: wear your bulkiest shoes on travel days. Never pack them in the bag if you can wear them on your feet. Inside each shoe, stuff a rolled pair of socks — using dead space inside footwear is one of the simplest carry-on packing hacks.',
